hook.real_world_problem:
Your product catalog needs a real database. Without Spring Data JPA:

```java
// Old way — JDBC (raw SQL):
Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(jdbcUrl, user, pass);
PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(
    "SELECT id, name, price FROM products WHERE id = ?");
ps.setString(1, productId);
ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery();
if (rs.next()) {
    return new Product(rs.getString("id"), rs.getString("name"), rs.getDouble("price"));
}
// Close connection... handle exceptions... repeat for EVERY query
```

**With Spring Data JPA:**
```java
// 1. Mark the class as a table:
@Entity
@Table(name = "products")
public class Product {
    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.UUID)
    private String id;
    private String name;
    private double price;
    // getters/setters or use Lombok
}

// 2. Declare a repository interface — zero implementation:
public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, String> {
    List<Product> findByCategory(String category);
    List<Product> findByPriceLessThan(double maxPrice);
    Optional<Product> findByName(String name);
}

// 3. Use it:
@Autowired ProductRepository repo;
repo.save(product);              // INSERT or UPDATE
repo.findById("P001");          // SELECT WHERE id = ?
repo.findByCategory("Electronics"); // SELECT WHERE category = ?
repo.deleteById("P001");        // DELETE WHERE id = ?
repo.findAll();                  // SELECT * FROM products
```

Zero SQL. Zero connection management. Spring Data generates the implementation at runtime.

concept_explanation.entity_mapping:
**@Entity — mapping Java to a database table:**

```java
import jakarta.persistence.*;  // JPA annotations

@Entity
@Table(name = "products")   // optional: default table name is class name
public class Product {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.UUID)  // auto-generate ID
    private String id;

    @Column(nullable = false, length = 200)  // NOT NULL VARCHAR(200)
    private String name;

    @Column(nullable = false)
    private double price;

    @Column(name = "category_code")  // maps to 'category_code' column
    private String category;

    @Column(updatable = false)  // set once, never updated
    private LocalDateTime createdAt;

    // JPA requires a no-arg constructor:
    protected Product() {}

    public Product(String name, double price, String category) {
        this.name = name; this.price = price; this.category = category;
        this.createdAt = LocalDateTime.now();
    }

    // getters (and setters if needed)
    public String getId()     { return id; }
    public String getName()   { return name; }
    public double getPrice()  { return price; }
    // ...
}
```

**Key JPA annotations:**
- `@Entity`: marks as a JPA entity (mapped to a table)
- `@Id`: the primary key field
- `@GeneratedValue`: how the ID is generated (UUID, AUTO, SEQUENCE, IDENTITY)
- `@Column`: customize column name, nullability, length
- `@Table`: customize table name

concept_explanation.jpa_repository:
**JpaRepository — free CRUD for any entity:**

```java
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;

@Repository  // optional — JpaRepository subinterfaces are detected automatically
public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, String> {
    // JpaRepository<EntityType, IdType> gives you:

    // ALREADY IMPLEMENTED (no code needed):
    // Product save(Product entity)                → INSERT or UPDATE
    // Optional<Product> findById(String id)       → SELECT WHERE id = ?
    // List<Product> findAll()                     → SELECT *
    // List<Product> findAllById(Iterable<String>) → SELECT WHERE id IN (?)
    // void deleteById(String id)                  → DELETE WHERE id = ?
    // boolean existsById(String id)               → SELECT EXISTS
    // long count()                                → SELECT COUNT(*)
    // void deleteAll()                            → DELETE FROM table
}
```

Spring Data generates the implementation at startup. You declare an interface — Spring provides a working class that makes real SQL.

concept_explanation.derived_queries:
**Derived query methods — Spring generates SQL from method names:**

```java
public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, String> {

    // Spring reads the method name and generates SQL:

    // SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = ?
    List<Product> findByCategory(String category);

    // SELECT * FROM products WHERE price < ?
    List<Product> findByPriceLessThan(double maxPrice);

    // SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = ? AND price <= ?
    List<Product> findByCategoryAndPriceLessThanEqual(String cat, double max);

    // SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%?%'
    List<Product> findByNameContainingIgnoreCase(String query);

    // SELECT * FROM products ORDER BY price DESC
    List<Product> findAllByOrderByPriceDesc();

    // SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = ? ORDER BY price ASC LIMIT ?
    List<Product> findTop10ByCategoryOrderByPriceAsc(String category);

    // SELECT COUNT(*) WHERE category = ?
    long countByCategory(String category);

    // SELECT EXISTS WHERE name = ?
    boolean existsByName(String name);
}
```

Keywords: `findBy`, `countBy`, `existsBy`, `deleteBy` + field names + `And`, `Or`, `LessThan`, `GreaterThan`, `Between`, `Containing`, `StartingWith`, `IgnoreCase`, `OrderBy`, `TopN`.

concept_explanation.custom_queries:
**Custom JPQL queries with @Query:**

```java
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.Query;
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.Modifying;
import org.springframework.data.repository.query.Param;

public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, String> {

    // JPQL — works with entity field names, not column names:
    @Query("SELECT p FROM Product p WHERE p.price BETWEEN :min AND :max")
    List<Product> findByPriceRange(@Param("min") double min, @Param("max") double max);

    // Native SQL — for complex queries:
    @Query(value = "SELECT * FROM products WHERE category = :cat ORDER BY RAND() LIMIT 5",
           nativeQuery = true)
    List<Product> findRandomByCategory(@Param("cat") String category);

    // Modifying query (UPDATE/DELETE) needs @Modifying:
    @Modifying
    @Query("UPDATE Product p SET p.price = p.price * :factor WHERE p.category = :cat")
    int adjustPrices(@Param("factor") double factor, @Param("cat") String category);
}
```

concept_explanation.data_jpa_test:
**@DataJpaTest — testing repositories:**

```java
import org.springframework.boot.test.autoconfigure.orm.jpa.DataJpaTest;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;

@DataJpaTest  // loads ONLY JPA components + in-memory H2
              // does NOT load controllers, services, etc.
class ProductRepositoryTest {

    @Autowired ProductRepository repo;

    @Test
    void save_andFindById_returnsProduct() {
        Product p = new Product("Mouse", 799, "Electronics");
        Product saved = repo.save(p);

        assertNotNull(saved.getId());
        Optional<Product> found = repo.findById(saved.getId());
        assertTrue(found.isPresent());
        assertEquals("Mouse", found.get().getName());
    }

    @Test
    void findByCategory_electronics_returnsTwoProducts() {
        repo.save(new Product("Mouse",    799,  "Electronics"));
        repo.save(new Product("Keyboard", 1999, "Electronics"));
        repo.save(new Product("Chair",    5000, "Furniture"));

        List<Product> electronics = repo.findByCategory("Electronics");
        assertEquals(2, electronics.size());
    }

    @Test
    void findByPriceLessThan_returns_correctCount() {
        repo.save(new Product("Mouse",   799,  "Electronics"));
        repo.save(new Product("Monitor", 18999,"Electronics"));

        assertEquals(1, repo.findByPriceLessThan(1000).size());
    }
}
```

@DataJpaTest: creates an H2 database, runs Hibernate, loads only @Repository beans. Very fast — no full Spring context.

